args: ＂His lawful wedded wife shall be me,\nthe witch. Now uh...seize her and stuff.＂
CUT! Just because this is rehearsal doesn't\nmean you can give it less than your best!
Ranzal, you need to sound more nasty!\nThat way people will understand the\ncentral theme of evil being punished!
Er, ain't this a love story?
And you! Lackeys! Put some heart\nand enthusiasm into your response!
Perhaps we could even replace the plain\n＂right＂ with the growl of a fiend.
I get that you're enthusiastic and all,\nbut if you start making changes like that,\nthis is gonna get weird fast.
Perhaps you are correct. My apologies.
It's all right—it just shows how serious\nyou are about fulfilling your true wish.
I was curious what you'd come up with\nafter you mentioned it...
But I never expected you'd want to\nput on a play for the orphanage.
Indeed, this is the work of a\ntrue priestess of Ilia!
My position in the church has nothing to do\nwith this. I am merely following my heart.
Now, less talking and more practicing!
We must deliver happiness\nunto each and every child!
I'm so grateful to you for doing this for the\nchildren, Hildegarde. I couldn't believe my\nears when you told me.
What kinda play is it gonna be?
Do bad guys get beaten up?! Huh?!
Heh. We shall endeavor not to\nlet all of you down. ...Hmm?
Saul, who is that girl over there,\nand why is she on her own?
Oh yeah, that's Eve.\nShe pretty much keeps to herself.
She's a pleasant, well-mannered child,\nbut she seems to prefer being alone.
I suppose I did act in rather the\nselfsame manner...
But that means she might not actually\nenjoy being alone at all.
She likely feels she cannot join in with\nthe others, lest she embarrass herself.
And so she is left with the belief that\nonly the goddess can free her.
That is how I was, at least.
Then that makes you the perfect person\nto help her out.
It sounds like you understand her\nfeelings better than anyone.
If this play is intended to make everyone\nhappy, that includes Eve, right?
...This is proving harder than I thought.\nShe's not letting me get close at all.
She's a clever child who clearly knows\nwhat the adults around her are thinking.
I just need a way to break the ice.

Perhaps something akin to how I was
caught up in everyone's Valentine's
enthusiasm, which is how I ended up
wearing this dress. Or perhaps...
Everyone who wants to play the princess,\nraise your hand!
And who wants to play the prince?!
There's no need to be so dismissive of\nsomething you've never tried. Your mind\nwill never be able to change otherwise.

In this play, there can be as many people
playing each role as there is demand.
You can be whatever—or whoever—
you so desire to be.
So then! What will you be?
I... I'd like to be a princess.\nBut someone like me could never...
If you lack confidence, you should seek to\nimprove yourself and work from there.
Is it really okay if I act with everyone?\nCan I really be a princess?
All right, time to start getting ready.\nThis way, everyone.
Oooo-kay, we've basically got an entire\ncast of princes and princesses now.\nYou sure you're okay with this?
They're totally gonna overshadow you,\nno matter HOW smokin' your dress is.
This whole play thing started because you\nwanted to be a princess, remember?
Um, did I say something weird?
No, Notte—and I appreciate your concern.\nBut I'm happy to let the children take\nwhatever role they desire.
When I was growing up, all I did was\npray. But now I'm an adult, and a\nsenior priestess to boot.
I cannot stay a princess awaiting rescue\nfor the rest of my days.
I would rather use my experiences\nto help someone else instead.
